REQUIREMENTS

The GNU Scientific Library (http://www.gnu.org/software/gsl).
For instance, in a Fedora Core Linux system you can install it using yum:

# yum install gsl gsl-devel

Other required packages:

xorg-x11-devel
freeglut-devel

The performance of some linear algebra computations significantly increases using ATLAS
(http://math-atlas.sourceforge.net/).

For Fedora Core 4 you can install it using yum: 

# yum install atlas

or better:

# yum install octave

which includes other useful packages such as atlas, fftw, gnuplot, etc.

(You can also download precompiled atlas libraries from https://sourceforge.net/project/showfiles.php?group_id=23725)

INSTALLATION

$ runhaskell Setup.hs configure --prefix=$HOME
$ runhaskell Setup.hs build
$ runhaskell Setup.hs install --user

You should also repeat these steps after a darcs pull.


COMMAND LINE EXAMPLES
---------------------

Interactive:

$ ghci demo.hs

Compiled:

$ ghc demo.hs -o demo -package GSL

With Atlas optimization, in Fedora Core 4:

We may need a symbolic link to the dynamic library:
$ ln -s /usr/lib/atlas/libcblas.so.3 libcblas.so

Then we change in GSLHaskell.cabal the line

- extra-libraries:    gsl gslcblas
+ extra-libraries:    gsl cblas

and reinstall the library.

Compiled using the static libraries downloaded from the home page:

$ chmod u+x setup
$ ./setup
$ LIBATLAS=/path/to/atlas/lib
$ ghc --make <yourprog.hs> GSL/gslaux.o -L$LIBATLAS -lcblas /usr/lib/libgsl.a -latlas

You can alternatively link with GSL/debuggslaux.o to "printf" the
C wrappers that are used by your program, with timing information.

